_Design thinking for socio-hydrological research_
*Introduction*
Design thinking is a creative process for solving problems. The approach puts
humans at the centre, encouraging practitioners to focus on the people for whom
the solutions are being developed, with the assumption that this will have
better results than approaches which focus on other aspects of product
development. Water sciences are fundamentally people-focused: as a society, our
interest in water arises from our dependence on it. Models are fundamental to
the water sciences, allowing us to predict the hydrological response of
catchments where no observations exist (time or space). More fundamentally,
models may be seen as hypotheses about the system behaviour. 

A variety of guides on hydrological modelling have been developed. The modelling
process has been formalised over the years. A well understood approach is the
perceptual-conceptual-computational framework set out by Keith Beven. In this
approach, the modeller first develops... 

Traditional hydrological models have viewed human behaviour as boundary
conditions. Socio-hydrology views humans as an intrinsic part of the water cycle
which must be included in order to understand the hydrology of a place. Models
have emerged as an essential tool in socio-hydrology.

This paper argues for design thinking as a way of developing perceptual models
for socio-hydrological research. 

