JULES set-up
For the India JULES application we need to simulate irrigation in each of the
three growing seasons and for surface and groundwater schemes. We need to be
able to show the potential impact of recharge from canal irrigation on the
seasonal water balance.

Relevant parameters:
JULES_SURFACE_TYPES:
ncpft = n (where n is the number of crop types we need to simulate)
JULES_VEGETATION:
l_prescsow = TRUE (prescribe crop sowing dates in JULES_CROP_PROPS)
l_irrig_dmd = TRUE (switch controlling the implementation of irrigation demand
code)
l_irrig_limit = FALSE (irrigation is unconstrained)
irr_crop = 1 (irrigation determined from Doell & Siebert (2002) data)
JULES_IRRIG
...

We use the JULES land surface model to resolve the surface water balance. Our
objective is to quantify the extent to which surface water irrigation may
recharge the underlying aquifer. Crop development is simulated using the the
built-in crop model. Where irrigation is specified, JULES continuously tops up
the top two soil layers to a critical point during the irrigation season. For
legacy reasons the specification of the irrigation season does not correspond
with that of the growing season in the crop model. To overcome this limitation
we specify the irrigation season to last all year (irr_crop=0). A further
limitation of the irrigation module is that while users are allowed to specify
the tiles in which irrigation occurs, the volume of water required to raise the
soil moisture to the critical point in these tiles is actually averaged across
the gridbox (Mathieson et al. 2019).

1. JULES simulation /without/ irrigation
2. JULES simulation /with/ irrigation across all tiles and all of the time

