** Research weather indices for crop insurance
Crop insurance is seen as a key component of resilience (?). While large farms
are often covered by conventional insurance policies, the coverage of
smallholders, especially in developing countries, is far lower. Conventional
insurance policies are inappropriate for developing countries, "where limited
commercialization and small average farm sizes are a major hindrance to the
sustainable development of commercial agricultural insurance products". 

The basic idea behind weather index insurance as opposed to conventional
insurance is to use an index variable as a proxy for losses, rather than
assessing the losses of each policyholder individually. "The sum insured is
normally based on production cost on an agreed value basis (fixed in the policy
in advance), and payouts are made based on a preestablished scale set out in the
insurance policy..." (World Bank, 2011). Under a typical weather index insurance product the insurance provider does not
need to visit a farm in order to "assess damages and arbitrate claims." Instead,
the insurance provider will pay out if the index variable is below an agreed threshold. The relative simplicity of the claim
process means that farmers covered by index-based insurance policies typically
receive payments far sooner than under conventional insurance policies. In
itself this is a major benefit of weather-index insurance, because fast payouts
means that farmers do not have to sell assets or reduce their expenditure to
survive. A benefit of insurance in general is that farmers may be more likely to
apply for, and receive, a bank loans for investing in new on-farm technologies,
driving productivity. Recognizing this interlinkage, some weather index
insurance policies are part of a package which includes a loan to purchase
improved seed varieties (e.g. Osgood et al, 2007).

According to Osgood et al. (2007), index insurance addresses two problems
encountered in conventional crop insurance: "moral hazard (incentives for a
farmer to let a crop die in order to get an insurance payout) and adverse
selection (in which insurance is priced based on the risks of the entire
population but only the most vulnerable farmers purchase insurance)."

Crop models can be used to identify crop-specific thresholds on which to base
the insurance index.
Weather index insurance products depend on the choice of index variable, which
must be a reliable proxy for crop yield. According to the World Bank (2011), it
must have the following attributes:
- Observable and easily measured
- Objective
- Transparent
- Independently verifiable
- Reported in a timely manner
- Consistent over time
- Experienced over a wide area

Water is crucial for crop development. Unless the crop receives irrigation,
rainfall is the main source of water during crop development. It is the most
common variable used in weather-index based insurance. However, a number of
variables besides rainfall influence crop development. Soil moisture is the
amount of water held in the soi. An insurance index based on soil moisture is
attractive because it combines several factors which influence crop development.
"Farmers receive indemnity/compensation whenever relative evapotranspiration
falls below 5% of historical long-running decadal relative evapotranspiration
data. The threshold for full payment is adjusted depending on areas and crop
development period."

There are some important considerations for ensuring the product is sustainable
and scalable. One is to "build capacity for local design and adaptation of
contracts as existing needs change and new needs are identified." In TWIGA, we
will rely on the expertise of GAIP to ensure the product is considerate of local
requirements. Further, there is a role for seasonal weather forecasts in the
insurance strategy. This is particularly important where insurance policy is
part of a package which includes a loan for seeds: ideally in this case the
selected seed variety would be suited to the expected conditions. Index
contracts should take into account relevant global and regional climate
processes, especially teleconnections, which 

It would be reasonable to specify a maximum distance from a weather station for
eligibility for insurance (e.g. Osgood et al, (2007) recommended a maximum
distance of 20km from a weather station). Clearly this arbitrarily excludes
farmers from accessing the policy. Ostensibly, a simple solution would be to
install more rain gauges to increase coverage. Besides national weather
services, a number of third parties are engaged in this activity, such as
TAHMO. Alongside these efforts, satellite data offers a promising alternative
source of data which can be used to spatially interpolate meteorological data
between stations.

One of the problems with using rainfall as an index is that it does not properly
account for the intensity of rainfall events within a specified time period
(e.g. dekadal). Hence, while the amount of rainfall during a dekad may exceed
the payout threshold, the amount of water may not meet the crop water
requirements due to losses such as runoff and surface evaporation. Climate
change, which is expected to result in the intensification of the hydrological
cycle in the tropics, may exacerbate the problem. Soil moisture is a more
reliable index of crop development because it implicitly accounts for these
hydrological processes.

In common with previous index insurance products, the contract is based on
dekadal (10 day) summaries of soil moisture deficit. 

Each contract includes a sowing window designated in terms of a start and end
dekad. The insurance contract begins during the first dekad in the sowing window
in which the soil moisture /deficit/ falls /below/ a certain threshold (the
"sowing trigger"). If the soil moisture deficit exceeds the threshold in each
dekad of the sowing window then it is assumed that the seed does not germinate
and a "failed sowing condition is signaled, a failed
sowing payment is paid, and the contract is terminated." If, on the other hand,
the threshold is reached then the contract starts in the dekad in which this
occurred. The contract itself is divided into /n/ (usually three) phases which each
contain several dekads.

